[[Henry Ogg Forbes|Henry Forbes]] described the Chatham Islands shag as ''Phalacrocorax onslowi'' in 1893, although it had been mentioned at the [[Royal Society Te Apārangi]] in 1871 by [[William Travers (New Zealand politician)]], sharing field notes from his son [[Henry Travers (naturalist)]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Notes on the Chatham Islands, extracted from Letters from Mr. H. H. Travers. |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/periodicals/TPRSNZ1871-4.2.6.1.2.3 |access-date=2024-10-22 |website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz}}</ref> The specific name commemorates [[William Onslow, 4th Earl of Onslow]], who was the [[Governor of New Zealand]] between 1889 and 1892.<ref name="Jobling">{{cite web|last1=Jobling|first1=J. A.|title=Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology|url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/key-to-scientific-names-in-ornithology?name=onslowi|website=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive|publisher=Lynx Edicions|editor-first=J.|editor-last=del Hoyo|editor2-first=A.|editor2-last=Elliott|editor3-first=D.|editor3-last=Christie|editor4-first=J.|editor4-last=Sargatal|access-date=25 March 2019|location=Barcelona|date=2019}}</ref>

The question of which genus to place the species in has, like the general question of the taxonomy of the cormorants and shags on the whole, been a long-standing mystery. It was long retained in ''[[Phalacrocorax]]'' along with the rest of the family when the family was treated as monogeneric. It was also placed in the genus ''Euleucocarbo'' along with the other "blue-eyed shags" found in New Zealand. The species has sometimes been considered a subspecies of an enlarged [[New Zealand king shag]] species (''Leucocarbo carunculatus'').<ref name="hbw">{{cite journal | last1=Orta | first1=J | last2=Christie | first2=D | last3=Jutglar | first3=F |last4=Kirwan | first4=G. M. |editor1-last=del Hoyo |editor1-first=Josep |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=Andrew |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=Jordi |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=David A |editor5-last=de Juana |editor5-first=Eduardo |year=2019 |title=  Chatham Shag (''Leucocarbo onslowi'') |journal=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |url=https://www.hbw.com/species/chatham-shag-leucocarbo-onslowi |publisher=Lynx Edicions |location=Barcelona | doi=10.2173/bow.chisha1.01.1 | s2cid=242270837 |access-date=25 March 2019 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Most recently a 2014 study of the [[mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] and [[nuclear DNA]] of the family placed it within the New Zealand blue-eyed shags and the other Antarctic blue-eyed shags in the genus ''[[Leucocarbo]]''.<ref name="Kennedy" /> This arrangement has also been adopted by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]].<ref name="ioclist">{{cite web | editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Hamerkop, Shoebill, pelicans, boobies, cormorants | work=World Bird List Version 9.1 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/pelicans/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=30 March 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423214825/https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/pelicans/ | archive-date=23 April 2020 }}</ref> The same study found that its closest relative was the species formerly known as Stewart shag.<ref name="Kennedy">{{cite journal |last1=Kennedy |first1=Martyn |last2=Spencer |first2=Hamish G. |title=Classification of the cormorants of the world |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |date=October 2014 |volume=79 |pages=249–257 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2014.06.020 |pmid=24994028 |bibcode=2014MolPE..79..249K }}{{dead link|date=May 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Since 2016, the Stewart shag is now treated as two species, the [[Otago shag|Otago]] and [[Foveaux shag]]s. The same study that split these two species also found that the Chatham Islands shag is closely related to the Otago shag and that this pair are in turn a sister clade to the Foveaux shag.<ref name="Stewart">{{Cite journal|last2=Scofield|first2=R. Paul|last3=Spencer|first3=Hamish G.|last4=Lalas|first4=Chris|last5=Easton|first5=Luke J.|last6=Tennyson|first6=Alan J.D.|last7=Adams|first7=Mark|last8=Pasquet|first8=Eric|last9=Fraser|first9=Cody|year=2016|title=Genetic and morphological evidence for two species of ''Leucocarbo'' shag (Aves, Pelecaniformes, Phalacrocoracidae) from southern South Island of New Zealand|journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society|last1=Rawlence|first1=Nicolas J.|last10=Waters|first10=Jonathan M.|last11=Kennedy|first11=Martyn|doi=10.1111/zoj.12376|volume=177|issue=3|pages=676–694|doi-access=free}}</ref> These three species are in turn related to the New Zealand king shag and an [[extinction|extinct]] ''Leucocarbo'' species, the Kohatu shag, from the far north of New Zealand.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rawlence |first1=Nicolas J. |last2=Till |first2=Charlotte E. |last3=Easton |first3=Luke J. |last4=Spencer |first4=Hamish G. |last5=Schuckard |first5=Rob |last6=Melville |first6=David S. |last7=Scofield |first7=R. Paul |last8=Tennyson |first8=Alan J.D. |last9=Rayner |first9=Matt J. |last10=Waters |first10=Jonathan M. |last11=Kennedy |first11=Martyn |title=Speciation, range contraction and extinction in the endemic New Zealand King Shag complex |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |date=2017 |volume=115 |pages=197–209 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2017.07.011 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/319065267 |pmid=28803756 |bibcode=2017MolPE.115..197R }}</ref>

"Chatham Islands shag" has been designated as the official common name for the species by the IOC.<ref name="ioclist"/> The species is also known as the "Chatham Island shag".<ref name="BNZ"/>

==Description==
An adult Chatham Islands shag is {{convert|63|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length and weighs around {{convert|1790|-|2400|g|abbr=on}}.<ref name="hbw"/> It is a large pied shag with a white throat, breast, belly and patches on the {{birdgloss|scapular|scapulars}} of the wings, and black or black-brown elsewhere. When breeding the head and hind-neck have a blue metallic sheen, the wings and {{birdgloss|mantle}} have a greenish sheen and the rest of the black areas have a purplish-blue sheen. The head has a prominent crest and there are white {{birdgloss|filoplume|filoplumes}} on the neck. Adults have a red {{birdgloss|gular skin|gular sac}} and orange-red caruncles on the face and the gape of the mouth. In spite of the common name of the genus the iris of the eye is brown, and the eye has a violet eye-ring. The bill is dark grey, with a bright red mouth, and the legs and feet are dull pink. Non-breeding birds look similar to breeding birds but are duller, have no crest or filoplumes, and duller bare parts. The caruncles are yellow, the eye-ring blue, the mouth orange and the bill is light-grey.<ref name="HANZAB"/>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Chatham Islands in New Zealand (zoom).svg|thumb|The Chatham Islands shag is, as its name suggests, endemic to the Chatham Islands of New Zealand.]]
The species is [[endemism|endemic]] to the [[Chatham Islands]], an archipelago around {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the east of New Zealand. In the Chathams it is an inshore species, rarely going more than a few kilometres away from shore, and it is more commonly found in sheltered water such as bays and inlets.<ref name="hbw"/>  It also forages in the large [[Brackish water|brackish]] [[Te Whanga Lagoon]].<ref name="BNZ">{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=M |editor1-last=Miskelly |editor1-first=Colin|title=Chatham Island shag |url=http://nzbirdsonline.org.nz/species/chatham-island-shag |website=New Zealand Birds Online |access-date=25 March 2019 |date=2013}}</ref> It breeds in [[bird colony|colonies]] on coastal areas and around Te Whanga Lagoon, either on flat areas, slopes or wide cliff ledges. There are currently thirteen colonies of this species, found on the main [[Chatham Island]] as well as [[Pitt Island]], [[Star Keys]], [[Rabbit Island (Chatham Islands)|Rabbit Island]] and North East Reef. These colonies are located close to the high-tide mark and can have as many as 300 nests in them.<ref name="2016 census">{{cite journal |last1=Bell |first1=M |last2=Bell |first2=D |last3=Boyle |first3=D |last4=Tuanui-Chisholm |first4=H |title=Chatham Island Shag census 2014–2016 |journal=Technical Report to the Department of Conservation. |date=2017 |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/globalassets/documents/conservation/marine-and-coastal/marine-conservation-services/reports/chatham-island-shag-census-2014-16-final-report.pdf}}</ref> It roosts on rocks close to shore or at sea,<ref name="hbw"/> although it may have different roosting sites for day and night. The species is non-migratory and has never been recorded away from the Chatham Islands,<ref name="HANZAB">{{cite book|editor2-last=Higgins|editor2-first=P. J.|editor1-last=Marchant|editor1-first=S.|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Volume 1: Ratites to ducks; Part B, Australian pelican to ducks. |date=1990| pages = 881–884 |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Melbourne|isbn=978-0-19-553068-1}}</ref> although the species does feed and roost on islands in the Chathams away from their breeding colonies, for example [[Mangere Island|Mangere]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nilsson |first1=R |last2=Kennedy |first2=E |last3=West |first3=J |title=The birdlife of South East Island (Rangatira), Chatham Islands, New Zealand |journal=Notornis |date=1994 |volume=41 |pages=109–125 |doi=10.63172/090693jenoyr |url=https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_41_sup_109.pdf}}</ref>

==Behaviour==
=== Diet and feeding ===
Like all cormorants, the Chatham Islands shag is a [[Seabird#Pursuit diving|pursuit-diver]], propelling itself underwater with its feet and returning to the surface to consume small prey caught in its bill.<ref name="hbw family">{{cite journal | last1=Orta | first1=J |editor1-last=del Hoyo |editor1-first=Josep |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=Andrew |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=Jordi |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=David A |editor5-last=de Juana |editor5-first=Eduardo |year=2019 |title=  Cormorants (''Phalacrocoracidae'') |journal=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |url=https://www.hbw.com/family/cormorants-phalacrocoracidae |publisher=Lynx Edicions |location=Barcelona | doi=10.2173/bow.phalac1.01 | s2cid=216251345 |access-date=26 March 2019 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The specific diet of the Chatham Islands shag is poorly known,<ref name="hbw"/> but is dominated by fish, including [[opalfish]], flatfish and [[Gobiomorphus|bullies]], as well as cephalopods such as octopuses, squid and cuttlefish. It generally feeds alone,<ref name="BNZ"/> but will form small feeding flocks at times.<ref name="hbw"/>

===Breeding===
Little is known about the breeding biology. Males attract a mate with an advertising display in which it stands with its tail cocked up and throws its neck and head back towards its tail, up to 13 times, while making a gargling noise. Mated pairs recognise each other at the nest with gaping and head-lowering displays. During these the male makes a barking noise, but the female is almost silent, making only a soft puffing noise.<ref name="HANZAB"/>

Breeding is seasonal, and the timing of laying can vary from colony to colony. Most Chatham Islands shags lay between October and December, but the colonies on Te Whanga Lagoon breed three months earlier than other colonies.<ref name="BNZ" /> The nest is made of [[Disphyma|iceplant]], grasses and other plants. Small nesting territories are defended from others of the species, and birds nesting in the centre of the colony have to run the gauntlet of biting to reach their nests as they pass other territories.<ref name="HANZAB"/> Two to four eggs are laid;<ref name="BNZ" /> the eggs measure {{convert|59|to(-)|63|mm|in|abbr=on}} × {{convert|37|to(-)|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} and are matt pale blue with a chalky covering.<ref name="HANZAB"/> The incubation time is not known but is thought to be around 30 days.<ref name="BNZ" />

==Conservation==
The Chatham Islands shag is threatened by a range of human activities and threats. The species is sensitive to disturbance at its breeding colonies, as nests are trampled by stampeding adults and nests are opportunistically raided by [[silver gull]]s after the eggs are unattended.  At worst, entire colonies have been abandoned due to disturbance by people or stock. Colonies on the main islands are also vulnerable to [[introduced species|introduced predators]] such as [[weka]], [[feral cat]]s and [[Common brushtail possum|possum]]s.  It is considered [[critically endangered species|critically endangered]] by the [[IUCN]].<ref name="iucn status 17 November 2021" />

